removed it
Why you need to have a declaration for static function?

It is defined at last, so added as forward declaration to avoid the compilation error since it is calling inside getDDR5DimmSize() which is before the definition of getNumOfEvenAndOddNumbrsInGivenNum().

done

yeah, added the missing line (i.e bit shifting)

As mentioned in other comment, it was for better clarity and readability instead of using magic numbers and also in future if we want use the same function for different range of numbers like 2 to 10 or 0 to 100 or 10 to 50 etc we can reuse it with just by adding the new argument to function and assigning that to this variable. Any way I removed it we can see at that time
Why you need to have a local variable here assigned with "num", when neither highRange is being modified nor num is being modified.

Since these are local variables and they doesn't exist once the function is returned so thought of taking local variables to have better readability instead of using directly the function arguments. anyway I removed them and using function argument name itself.
Please consider the comments for changes required. Thanks.
SVPD_JEDEC_DDR5_RESVD_BYTE should be good here.
For better readability I have added for individual parameters instead of having generic constant definitions for all. should be fine I feel.
Already MASK has the readable name so shifting may need right names described in SPEc.
I have taken reference of existing constant name i.e JEDEC_DIE_COUNT_RIGHT_SHIFT to define the name for shifting so the name suggested by you won't sounds good here so will keep this name only.
Please reuse already defined constants.

Can be done, but for better clarity and better readability I thought of defining the individual names for each parameters instead of defining one constant and reusing it for every where. I think this should be ok.
If you feel this gives better clarity then replace other constant name instead, but having two for same purpose doesn't serve the purpose.
Ack
Both can be covered in SVPD_JEDEC_DDR5_RESVD_BYTE.
For better readability I have added for individual parameters instead of having generic constant definitions for all. should be fine I feel.
Same as above.
I have taken reference of existing constant name i.e JEDEC_DIE_COUNT_RIGHT_SHIFT to define the name for shifting so the name suggested by you won't sounds good here so will keep this name only.
Many of the if checks, all including below seems invalid on the basis of the MASK as tmp can't exceed the value after right shift. Also, it's unnecessary, as it can't happen due to MASKING.

It can happen, what if we get the value 10 or 11 after masking and shifting. so to handle the invalid range this if check is necessary. allowed values are 00 & 01 so to handle invalid values (10 & 11) this check has been added.
Except package RANK others are same with Asymmetric Even so can have it common.
done

changed as discussed.

Above comment applies here.

These should be suffice for even rank calculation.
changed as discussed.
The calculation should be for '*' based than '/' please refer DDr4 for calculation.
changed as discussed.
Ack
Same as above comment refer DDR4 for calculation.
changed as discussed.
Reviewed thoroughly. arithmetic calculation in most of the places looks ok, except the ones commented.
you can reuse the existing JEDEC_PRI_BUS_WIDTH_MASK.

can be done, but using existing name will mislead though values are same, hence I have defined new names for readability purpose. This is done by Jinu too in ISDMM code as well he has defined new name for DDR5 with same values. we will keep it as it is.

in your change, whatever variable you mentioned as reserved_value, are actually not the reserved values. they are the max possible values. 
eg: JEDEC_NUM_OF_CHNL_PER_DIMM_RESERVED_VALUE=1 -> 1 isn't the reserved value here. 2 and 3 are the reserved values. you can reword it as JEDEC_NUM_OF_CHNL_PER_DIMM_MAX_POSSIBLE OR any meaningful name of your choice.

you can make this change wherever required
Modified and used the names as per the existing code for DDR4 .
can you please try to reuse the existing constexpr. here you can make use of JEDEC_RESERVED_BITS. Please avoid polluting const expressions.  Try to reuse as much as possible.

can be done, but using existing name will mislead though values are same, hence I have defined new names for readability purpose. This is done by Jinu too in ISDMM code as well he has defined new name for DDR5 with same values. we will keep it as it is.
these three parameters will be both [in, out], as we are using its value[as input] in this api and updating [output]

These parameters description is specific to this function arguments, for this function the mentioned parameters are output parameters only since the values for these are getting filled inside this function.

sdramIoWid parameter should be [in,out] as you are utilising it as input at line201.
check this https://stackoverflow.com/questions/47732665/is-that-an-in-or-in-out-parameter-doxygen-c
why do we need this check? can you point me such condtions in spec?
if you see in the spec, actually value 1 (001) is reserved and value 5(101) onwards all values are reserved hence 2 checks have been added here. Please check Byte 4 in spec for reference.
ok.
you can return 1 directly without line 231
ok, did in other way, i.e changed the default value of retVal=1 and returning 0 directly in failure scenarios

where are you calculating die per package and sdram density per die for asymmetric odd case.
ie, die per package-> for asymm odd case -> taken from Byte 8 (bits 7~5)
and sdram density per die -> for asymm odd case -> taken from Byte 8 (4~0)

while making the common function for symmetrical module & asymmetric even rank mistakenly I removed and used the common function here too, will revert the parameter extraction part for asymmetric odd rank.

In cerr can you please mention the dimm eeprom path for which the failure happened.
please update every cerr statements (wrt your changes only)with eeprom path.
we don't get the dimm eeprom path to print, we just log an error as like DDR4 code

can you please change type of noOfChanlPerDimm to size_t? this might create issue.
On a 64-bit system, the size_t will be 64-bit, but unsigned int will be 32 bit. So we cannot use them interchangeably.
changed for all parameters of type uint8_t to size_t  for safer side.
can you please add for which dimm eeprom the calculation failed..
we don't get the dimm eeprom path to print, we just log an error as like DDR4 code
can you please add a comment before line 264, like "you are calculating primary bus width [in terms of bits] based on the value obtained".
All parameters we are calculating in terms of bits only as per SPEC, so no need add the comment specifically for this.

can you please explain why you need this line 283? when I manually calculate, this is not giving the result.

as per my calc,
tmp = iterator[MEM_BYTE_234] & JDEC_SDRAM_RANK_MIX_TYPE_MASK; 
and then
tmp >> 6
will give the right sdramType.

This is to check the 6th bit is enabled or not below is the explanation:
doing left shift of number 1 by 6 position and doing AND operation with the value of tmp. if 6th bit is set means asymmetrical else symmetrical.

why are you sending same input twice to getSdramParamsFromSPDData(), just in the name of primary and secondary? [lines 310 and 321 ]

anyways gonna get same output right?
the calculation is different for second SDRAM, as part of one of the above comments its been addressed, I mean the calculation of second SDRAM parameters separated from the common function.

and also print the value of sdramtype obtained.

we don't get the dimm eeprom path to print, we just log an error as like DDR4 code.
